%T A394625 10,207,0,225,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,36,-1,-1,-1,103,52,-1,-1,-1,9,96,-1,
%U A394625 500,148,524,-1,-1,-1,156,17,419,76,-1,-1,-1,1586,8,-1,13537,0,-1,-1,110,-1,-1,-1,21,12,-1,985,-1,1015,-1,-1,89,-1,46,-1,140,-1,-1,-1,16,-1,6,-1
%N A394625 Largest y solution to Mordell's equation y^2 = x^3 - n for some integer x, -1 if no such y exists.
%F A394625 a(n) = sqrt(A394624(n)^3 - n) iff A394624(n) > 0, a(n) = 1 if A394624(n) = 0.
%F A394625 a(k^3) = 0 for k = 1, 2, 3, 4, ... but not always, cf. examples.
%e A394625 For n = 1, A394624(n) = 1 is the largest x for which x^3 - 1 = 0 = a(1)^2 is a square, with a(1) = 0.
%e A394625 For n = 2, A394624(n) = 3 is the largest x for which x^3 - 2 = 25 = a(2)^2 is a square, with a(2) = 5.
%e A394625 For n = 3, 5, 6, ... (cf. A081121) Mordell's equation y^2 = x^3 - n has no integer solution, so a(n) = -1.
%e A394625 For n = 4, A394624(n) = 5 is the largest x for which x^3 - 4 = 121 = a(4)^2 is a square, with a(4) = 11. (There is also a smaller solution, 2^3 - 4 = 2^2, with x = 2, y = +-2.)
%e A394625 For n = k^3 we always have the solution x = k, y = 0, but for example when k = 6, then x = 10 gives 10^3 - 6^3 = 2^3*(5-3)*(5^2+5*3+3^2) = 2^4*7^2 = 28^2, and for k = 7 we have x = 8 with 8^3 - 7^3 = 64 + 56 + 49 = 13^2 and also x = 14 with 14^3 - 7^3 = 7*7^2*(2^2+2+1) = 7^4 which generalizes to other multiples of 7.
%o A394625 (PARI) apply( {A394625(n,L=20*n^2)=if(L=ellratpoints(ellinit([0, 0, 0, 0, -n]), [L, 1]),-L[#L][2],-1)}, [1..99]) \\ Search limit L corresponds to Hall's conjecture with over-estimate of the largest known ratio sqrt(x)/n ~ 4.26.
%Y A394625 Cf. A394624 (corresponding x values), A081120 (number of integral solutions to y^2 = x^3 - n), A134109 (only those with y >= 0), A081121 (n for which there are no integral solutions), A081119 (number of integral solutions to y^2 = x^3 + n).
%K A394625 sign,new
%O A394625 1,2
